      "title": "The Weight of Copper",
      "date": "2024-11-08",
      "type": "poetry",
      "slug": "001",
      "content": "I learned about resistance in a classroom,\nhow every wire fights the current,\nhow the world charges a price\nfor every electron that passes through.\n\nNo one told me\nthe same law applies\nto people.\n\nThe greater the resistance,\nthe more heat you generate —\nand I have been running so hot\nfor so long\nthat my insulation is wearing thin.\n\nI sat with an ohmmeter once,\npressing its probes to a length of copper wire,\nwatching the display blink: 0.3 Ω.\nBarely a fight.\nJust smooth and unbroken passage.\n\nI have never been copper.\nI am something with a much higher resistance —\nthe kind that wastes energy as heat,\nthe kind that glows red before it breaks.\n\nBut perhaps that is something too.\nTo glow.\nEven briefly.\nEven alone."
